context: In <a0_0>1918<a0_0/> Whitehead's academic responsibilities began to seriously expand as he accepted a number of high administrative positions within the <a1_0><a4_0>University of London<a1_0/> system<a4_0/>, of which Imperial College London was a member at the time. He was elected <a2_0><a5_0>Dean of the Faculty of Science<a5_0/><a2_0/> at the <b11_0>University of London<b11_0/> in late 1918 (a post he held for four years), a member of the University of London's Senate in 1919, and <a6_0><b12_0>chairman of the Senate's Academic<b12_0/> (leadership) Council<a6_0/> in 1920, a post which he held until he departed for America in <a3_0><a7_0><b9_0>1924<b9_0/><a7_0/><a3_0/>. Whitehead was able to exert his newfound influence to successfully lobby for a new history of science department, help establish a <a8_0><b10_0>Bachelor of Science<b10_0/><a8_0/> degree (previously only Bachelor of Arts degrees had been offered), and make the school more accessible to less wealthy students.
